title: Grateful Dead Live at Fillmore West on 1970-06-07
description:
Set 1: Don't Ease Me In, Silver Threads And Golden Needles, Friend Of The Devil, Candyman, Cold Jordan, Swing Low Sweet Chariot, Cumberland Blues, Me & My Uncle, New Speedway Boogie

Set 2: Cryptical Envelopment > Drums > The Other One > Cryptical Envelopment > Drums > Sugar Magnolia, Louie Louie Jam, It's A Man's World, Mama Tried, Sitting On Top Of The World, Cosmic Charlie, Casey Jones, Good Lovin' > Drums > Good Lovin'

reviews.review_text:
good good good good free form 70s show, not much structure to it just good fun...the acoustic and quasi acoustic semi electic stuff is great lotta goodies in there

cool jam out of cryptical, interesting first sugar magnolia

Great Show and Interesting War Protest Speech Great show with excellent sound clarity!

In the middle of Drums, you can hear a female anti Vietnam protester voice tell the crowd that "We should get up off our F@$%ing A$$es and help the troops get out of there".  Wow, a piece of the times saved in that song, pretty powerful.

YIPPIE During the drums, not mic-ed, but either onstage or on the rail, someone gives a brief speech, stating "...members of the Youth International Party...brothers dying overseas...etc" Another person, could it be a band member or even JG gives a half-hearted right on just before they start The Other One. You can hear shreds of speech in the first minutes of the TOO then I guess the person was cleared out or retreated.
GREAT sound, GREAT period.
Peace, Bob
P.S. First Sugar Magnolia!
good show to start off the morning Cumberland, MAMU, Speedway.  Three of my favorite dead tunes back to back.

The Show Smokin', nailin' show for 1970, awesome sound quality too.

My Dog has no nose!

How dose he smell?

Bloomin' awful!

Cumberland is cut! I've never heard a live Cumberland that sounds so much like the Workingman's version. But it's missing a good few seconds or more at 2:46. Have to deduct a star.

Why can't we hear it the way they played it? Tracks 11 through 17 should be ONE TRACK! Minus  another star.

Come on guys! A 50 second 'tease' gets it's own track?!?! And every drum solo?!?!?

Side one of Anthem of The Sun lists 7 different tracks, but that doesn’t matter because there is no interruption between tracks. Can you imagine what it would be like if there were an interruption between St. Stephen and The Eleven on side two of Live/Dead?

Seriously, shouldn't this site offer a listening experience at least equal to my 44-year-old vinyl? Until the day that this site offers seamless advancement from one track to the next, cutting up The Other One into four (or more) tracks borders on the criminal.

Hey...the last 12 seconds of "Cryptical Envelopment/>Jam" sounds like PITB. Cut it up more! Make another track!

Grateful Happy to hear it.
Thank you.

Cold Jordan Oh sinner as you tread on life's journey, take Jesus as your daily guide 
Though you may feel pure and saintly, without Him walking by your side
But when you come to make the crossing at the ending of his pilgrim's way
If you ever will need your saviour, you will surely need him on that day
Now look at that cold Jordan, look at its deep water
Look at that wide river, oh hear the mighty billows roll
You better take Jesus with you, he's a true companion
Oh I'm sure without him that you never will make it home
That awful day of judgement is coming in the by and by
We'll see our Lord descending in glory from on high
Oh, let us keep in touch with Jesus and in the special love of God
And may we ever be called ready when he calls us over Jordan's tide
Now what you gonna do, oh what you gonna say
Oh how you gonna feel when you come to the end of the way?
----
SWEET CHARIOT- is kind as well.

it goes without saying It goes without saying this is magnificent.

Southern Comfort opened these shows and NRPS with Jerry played at set between the Dead's acoustic and electric sets, as on 6/4/70.

The cut in Cumberland Blues is probably Bear changing his 7 inch reel.

The shouting near the end of drums, mentioned below, reflects the truly dire times.  It was four weeks after Kent State, Vietnam was getting worse every day.  Dire dire times.  And the Dead working their magic spell, trying to rise and lift us with them.
